// The `prelude.json` sub-module: the JSON boundary, over PLAIN Katari values. A JSON document is not a
// dedicated tree type ‚Äî it is an ordinary value: a record / array / string / integer / number / boolean /
// null (the "document shape"). A program traverses a parsed reply with shape filters (`case record(r)` /
// `case array(a)` / `case string(s)`) and the total readers below, and builds one with ordinary record /
// array literals. Referenced by the default-import qualifier: `json.parse(...)`, `json.field(...)`.
//
// The naming law is the spine of this module: EVERY VERB KEEPS KEYS VERBATIM. `parse`, `parse_as` and
// `stringify` all move object keys exactly as written ‚Äî a `$`-prefixed key (`$ref`, `$constructor`) is an
// ordinary key, never a wire discriminator, and no key is ever escaped. There is no separate "wire word":
// `stringify` is the single text writer, and it is TOTAL over every value.
//
//   - `parse : string -> unknown`      text -> the document value (traverse it with shape filters)
//   - `parse_as[T] : string -> T`      literal parse + validation against T's schema (the typed text boundary)
//   - `stringify[T] : T -> string`     ANY value -> its (compact) JSON text, keys verbatim
//
// `stringify` is total and CANONICAL ‚Äî one value has exactly one text:
//   - a document (record / array / scalar) is written key-for-key, so `stringify(parse(s)) == s` (an
//     IDENTITY, modulo whitespace / number normalisation) and `parse(stringify(d)) == d` for a document d;
//   - a `file` becomes its `{ "$ref": id, "semanticKind": ‚Ä¶ }` handle object;
//   - a `data` value nests its fields under `value`: `{ "$constructor": name, "value": { ‚Ä¶fields } }`;
//   - an agent / closure / tool becomes its `$agent` / `$closure` / `$tool` handle object.
// Keys are shown VERBATIM either way (no `$$` escaping ‚Äî that device lives only inside the persistence
// codec's bytes, never at this surface), so a record with a literal `$ref` key is indistinguishable in the
// text from a `file` handle. That ambiguity is ACCEPTED, because `stringify` is also the READ CHANNEL that
// lets an AI SEE a handle / data value (an error render, a handle embed, a tool result shown back to a
// model). Whether an external API understands the `$`-tagged form of a handle is the CALLER's concern:
// `stringify` emits the canonical form, it does not promise the far side reads it back.
//
// There is no `decode` and no `encode`. A document is ALREADY a value, so reading one needs no wire step:
// a plain value (record / array / scalar / file) drops straight into a document tree, and a document read
// from the outside becomes a value verbatim. The one place a wire form must be REVIVED ‚Äî an AI replaying a
// `{ "$ref": ... }` handle into a tool argument that expects a `file` ‚Äî is the delegation boundary's job:
// `reflection.call_agent` validates the argument against the callee's schema, and revives a `$ref` into a
// real `file` exactly where the schema expects one (schema-directed, never a blind lift).
//
// Errors: malformed text throws `parse_error` (`parse` / `parse_as`); a document that does not conform to
// the requested type's schema throws `decode_error` (`parse_as`). `stringify` is TOTAL ‚Äî it never throws.

@"A JSON document failed to parse: the text is not JSON. Thrown by `parse` / `parse_as`."
data parse_error(message: string)

@"A document does not conform to the requested type's schema. Thrown by `parse_as`; `message` names the
offending path."
data decode_error(message: string)

@"Parse JSON text into its document value ‚Äî a record / array / string / integer / number / boolean / null,
keys kept exactly as written (`$` is not interpreted). Traverse it with shape filters (`case record(r)`)
and the readers below, or pin its shape with `parse_as[T]`. A number without a fractional part parses as
`integer`. Malformed text throws `parse_error`."
primitive agent parse(@"The text of one complete JSON document." text: string) -> unknown with prelude.throw[parse_error]

@"Parse JSON text directly as a T, validated against T's schema ‚Äî the typed text boundary, LITERAL like
`parse` (keys kept as written, `$` not interpreted). Instantiate T explicitly (it appears only in the
result, so it cannot be inferred). Malformed text throws `parse_error`; a schema mismatch throws
`decode_error` naming the offending path. A `$ref` an AI replayed is not revived here (this is literal) ‚Äî
that happens at the delegation boundary, where the target's schema says a `file` is expected."
primitive agent parse_as[T](@"The text of one complete JSON document." text: string) -> T with prelude.throw[parse_error | decode_error]

@"Render ANY value as its (compact) JSON text, keys kept exactly as written ‚Äî TOTAL and CANONICAL (one
value, one text). A document value (record / array / string / integer / number / boolean / null)
round-trips verbatim, so `stringify(parse(s))` is `s` up to whitespace; a `file` becomes its `$ref` handle
object, a `data` value nests its fields under `value` (`{ $constructor: name, value: { ...fields } }`), and
an agent / closure / tool its handle object. Nothing is escaped ‚Äî a `$`-prefixed record key shows as itself,
so a literal `$ref` key reads the same as a real handle. That ambiguity is ACCEPTED, because `stringify` is
also the READ CHANNEL for showing an AI a handle / data value (an error render, a handle embed, a tool
result rendered back to a model). Whether an external API understands the `$`-tagged form is the CALLER's
concern ‚Äî `stringify` emits the canonical form, it does not promise the far side reads it. A secret operand
taints the whole result (the monotonic information-flow rule)."
primitive agent stringify[T](value: T) -> string

// The total readers ‚Äî plain Katari over `unknown`, for picking values out of a document of unknown or
// irregular shape (an AI reply, a third-party API response) without a shape filter at every step. The
// subject parameter is named `target`, uniform with the other container lookups (`record.get`,
// `array.get`). Each reader is TOTAL: a missing key, an out-of-range index or a wrong shape yields `null` /
// `""` / an empty container rather than an error, so probes chain freely ‚Äî `text(target = field(target =
// element(target = parsed, index = 0), key = "content"))` ‚Äî and absence is checked once, at the end, where
// it matters. For a document whose shape IS known, prefer the typed boundary (`parse_as[T]`), which
// validates instead of defaulting. Where a genuine shape branch is wanted, use a shape filter
// directly (`match (node) { case record(r) -> ... case array(a) -> ... case _ -> node }`).

@"The record @target@ holds (its entries), or the empty record if @target@ is not a record."
agent entries(target: unknown) -> record[unknown] {
  match (target) {
    case record(record_value) -> record_value
    case _ -> record.empty()
  }
}

@"The array @target@ holds (its elements), or the empty array if @target@ is not an array."
agent items(target: unknown) -> array[unknown] {
  match (target) {
    case array(array_value) -> array_value
    case _ -> array.empty()
  }
}

@"The child at object key @key@ (`null` if @target@ is not a record or has no such key)."
agent field(target: unknown, key: string) -> unknown {
  match (target) {
    case record(record_value) -> record.get(target = record_value, key = key)
    case _ -> null
  }
}

@"The element at array index @index@ (`null` if @target@ is not an array or @index@ is out of range)."
agent element(target: unknown, index: integer) -> unknown {
  match (target) {
    case array(array_value) -> array.get(target = array_value, index = index)
    case _ -> null
  }
}

@"The string @target@ holds (the empty string if it is not a string)."
agent text(target: unknown) -> string {
  match (target) {
    case string(string_value) -> string_value
    case _ -> ""
  }
}
